Minimum parking requirements may be reduced according to the following strategies:
1. Walkable Commercial Contexts. In the B-1 and B-2 districts, any use under 2,000 square feet is exempt from providing on-site parking, and all other uses in the B-1 and B-2 districts may reduce the required on-site parking by 30% provided the project is designed in a compact, walkable format with smaller blocks and walkable streets.
2. On-street Parking Credit. All on-street parking within 600 feet of any lot frontage may count towards the parking requirement at a rate of one space for every three on-street spaces. However, any on-street parking in front of residential lots shall not count for nonresidential uses in the area.
3. Bicycle Parking Credit. All on-site bicycle parking may reduce the required vehicle parking at a rate of one space for every four bicycle parking spaces up to a maximum of 15% of the required vehicle parking.
4. Public Parking Credit. Any site within 600 feet of a public parking area may reduce the required vehicle parking at a rate of one space for every two public parking spaces.

Parking maximums are set at 120% of the minimums, but may be exceeded through several mitigation strategies.

Certain properties adjacent to the Old Downtown District are exempt from parking requirements if a specified number of spaces is maintained. 

On-street parking may be used to offset the required number of parking spaces. Historic buildings may receive a 50% reduction to the minimum parking requirement. 

There is a payment in lieu of parking options for up to three parking spaces required for any use in the Stuart Community Redevelopment Area.
The area known generally as the Central Business District and more particularly described as that area within the CB District, is exempt from minimum parking requirements.
Off street parking is not required in the DMX Downtown Mixed-Use District.
There are no minimum number of off-street parking spaces required in the C-2 General Commercial District except where the use is a conditional use.
The C-3 Central Commercial District is exempt from minimum parking requirements.

Albemarle has no fixed parking ratios for nearly all uses other than: ADUs (one space required), selected home-based occupations (lawyers, physicians, dentists, and chiropractors), church tent uses, auction houses, and some light industrial uses.
On November 9, 2023 the city of Taylor adopted the Taylor Made Land Development Code which eliminated parking mandates citywide for all uses.

Commercial and industrial uses may not provide more than 125% of the parking minimums.
The following area is exempt from off-street automobile parking requirements: Blocks 82, 83, 84, 90, 91, 92, 93, 96, 97, 98, 99, 100, 104, 105, 106 and 107, all in the original townsite of the city.

Within the MUI Mixed Use/Infill Development Overlay Zone off-street parking is not required where physical constraints make adherence to parking requirements infeasible. Otherwise parking must be provided.
Parking requirements are reduced by 50% in the Central Business (CB) District.

No minimum parking is required for new or redevelopment in the B-2 Central Business District. Minimum off-street parking requirements within the Mixed-Use Overlay District are one-half (1/2) of the required spaces. In districts where one hundred (100) or more parking spaces are required for a site, additional parking spaces may not exceed fifteen percent (15%) of the minimum requirement.

For mixed-use and nonresidential uses, any on-street parking located directly in front of the property may be counted towards on-site parking requirements. Furthermore, the number of required parking spaces may be reduced for uses providing bicycle parking at a ratio of up to one (1) off-street vehicle space reduction per two (2) bicycle spaces provided. The total number of required vehicle off-street parking spaces may not be reduced by more than five percent (5%) for any project.

Minimum parking regulations do not apply to lots located in a block within the C3 Service Commercial District which, at the time of passage of this zoning chapter, was occupied by structures used for commercial purposes totaling 50% or more of the area of the block.
Retail stores and banks under 1000 square feet are exempt from minimum parking requirements.

Phoenixville PA had the zoning ordinance rewritten to remove parking requirements for specific blocks of the downtown, and all other parking is required to be based on a parking demand analysis, not specific standards.
Off-street parking requirements do not apply for uses within the Central Business District.
On-street parking within 50 feet of the subject property boundaries may be included within off-street parking requirement calculations.
The total parking spaces provided may not exceed 150% of the minimum parking requirements, except for retail uses which may not exceed 125% of the minimum parking requirement.
All business zoned properties in the Old Morton District as shown on the map are exempt from the minimum parking requirements.

Minimum parking requirements may not be exceeded by more than 125% of the minimums, unless approved by the Community Development Director. Parking requirements may be reduced with the approval of the Community Development Director based on the proximity to public parking, bus stops, or a carsharing or vanpool program.
Parking maximums are set at 10% greater than the minimums.

Within the TOD-MU Zone, parking requirements are reduced by right for residential uses, and on-street parking may count towards the requirements for all uses. Parking maximums apply to nonresidential uses in the zone.

Off-street parking requirements are not applicable to land development in the downtown parking district.
Commercial uses in the E Commercial District are exempt from minimum parking requirements.

Theaters not exceeding ten thousand (10,000) square feet and retail establishments not exceeding three thousand (3,000) of floor area in downtown Clayton with the exception of the properties facing the north side of Maryland Avenue west of Forsyth Boulevard to the west City limits are exempt from minimum parking requirements. Restaurants located in the Central Business District not exceeding three thousand (3,000) square feet of gross floor area, cafeterias and kiosks located in office buildings designed to primarily serve the tenants of the building, restaurants located in office buildings or commercial spaces which have one hundred fifty thousand (150,000) gross square feet or more of floor area and which provide parking, and restaurants in hotels or motels are also exempt.

Within the B-2 central business district, a fee-in-lieu of required parking may be paid for the first seven spaces otherwise required. Additional spaces may be reduced through council approval of a further fee-in-lieu payment.

Minimum parking requirements do not apply to any re-occupancy of existing buildings or structures within the following area of the B-2 Central Business District:

The area bounded on the north by the alley north of Court Street; on the east by the alley east of Mauvaisterre Street; on the south by the alley south of Morgan Street; and on the west by the alley west of Sandy Street.

A reduction in the number of required off-street parking spaces for the re-use of an existing commercial building in any district may be authorized under a special use permit.
There is no minimum parking requirement for land uses on lots one-half acre or less in the Downtown District. Parking maximums are set at 140% of the minimums.
Nonresidential uses within the C General Commercial District are exempt from on-site parking requirements.
Off-street parking is not required in the B-1 Central Business District.
Parking requirements may be reduced through motorcycle parking.
The B-3 General Business District is exempt from minimum parking requirements.
Commercial uses are exempt from parking mandates.
The C-2 Central Business District is exempt from minimum parking requirements.
The Central Business District, as shown on the Zoning Map, is exempt from minimum parking requirements.
Anacortes reduced parking minimums for most uses and implemented discretionary review for other uses. New projects in downtown have an additional reduction of 50%
No off-street parking facilities are required for retail sales and retail service establishments of less than five hundred (500) square feet of floor area within the B-2 Central Business District.

Minimum parking requirements do not apply when application of the off-street parking provisions result in a requirement of three spaces or less on a single zoning lot in any business or manufacturing district.

The total number of accessory parking spaces provided for single-family, two-family or multiple-family dwellings may not exceed the requirements by more than fifty percent (50%) or four (4) spaces, whichever is greater.

Properties zoned mixed commercial (MC) are exempt from off-street parking requirements. For any use categorized as “Commercial” or “Industrial” in the “Off Street Parking Requirements” table, off-street parking spaces may not be provided in an amount that is more than 125 percent of the minimum requirements.
All business uses located within the B-2 Central Business District are exempt from off-street parking requirements.
No minimum number of parking spaces are required.  However, if parking is provided, there are standards, such as providing pedestrian-ways.
No off-street parking is required in the C-2 Central Business District, except where multi-family development is the principal use.

Properties within the B-2 Central Business District are exempt from minimum parking requirements. Maximum parking limits in the district are set at 50% of the normal minimums. Parking requirements may be reduced through the provision of motorcycle parking.

Within the C-1 Neighborhood convenience district, C-4 Commercial flex district, C-5 Commercial manufacturing district, and DT Downtown districts and with approval of the Zoning Administrator, on-street parking spaces may be counted toward the required off-street parking spaces. A fee in lieu for each credit is required for the C-4 and C-5 Districts. In addition, off-street public parking spaces may be counted toward the required off-street parking spaces. In the DB-1 Zoning District, no parking spaces or loading facilities are required for existing developed sites. Any on-street parking or public parking facilities not in connection to a public building, and within 300 feet of the property may be counted toward 50% of the total parking requirement.

The City Council can waive some or all of the use's "default" parking requirement if the property owner can demonstrate that they can partially or fully serve their building's transportation needs with nearby on-street parking, shared parking, bicycle parking, transit, pedestrian connectivity, etc.

report_summary: Within the H-1 Historic District, retail and commercial establishments have no minimum parking requirement, due to adequate parking in municipal parking lots and on-street parking.

Minimum parking requirements may be reduced according to the following strategies:
1.    Downtown. In the C-1 district, any use under 2,000 square feet is exempt from any on-site parking. All other uses in the C-1 district may reduce the required on-site parking by 40 percent, in addition to all other applicable credits and shared parking reductions.
2.    On-Street Parking Credit. All on-street parking within 600 feet of any lot frontage may count towards the parking requirement at a rate of one space for every three on-street spaces.
3.    Bicycle Parking Credit. All on-site bicycle parking may reduce the required vehicle parking at a rate of one space for every four bicycle parking spaces up to a maximum of 15 percent of the required vehicle parking.

Parking maximums exist for most multi-family residential and commercial uses.
Any use within the CBD, Kearney Center Mixed District is exempt from the off-street parking requirements.
The B-1 Business District is exempt from minimum parking requirements.
The City of Walla Walla has implemented an exemption of its off-street parking standards in its Central Business District
Nonresidential uses in the B-3 and B-4 Districts are exempt from minimum parking requirements.

There are no parking requirements within the industrial land uses. The City of Leduc reduced minimum parking requirements for nonresidential uses in the downtown as part of the Land Use Bylaw. Two-thirds of the normal parking minimum is required. In two overlays of the downtown, parking minimums may be waived altogether for non-residential uses

No parking is required for non-residential development in the CBD, except as may be required for special uses.
Parking requirements may be reduced through the availability of on-street parking and public parking in the CBD (for residential uses), CP, and CA Districts.
report_type: Eliminate Parking Minimums, Reduce Parking Minimums

report_summary: Any establishment located within the C-3 Central Commercial zone (or any other zone) is exempt from minimum parking requirements when participating in an approved Butte-Silver Bow parking district. A fee-in-lieu of required parking may be provided in the C-3 District.
report_type: Reduce Parking Minimums, Eliminate Parking Minimums

report_summary: Single-family dwellings may not provide more than 4 parking spaces unless a special use permit is obtained.
In the Central Business District, accessory off-street parking spaces are not required, except for buildings containing dwelling units or lodging rooms.
Panama City removed all parking minimum requirements on lots less than 10,000 sq. ft., buildings built before 1945, and all new construction less than 5 stories.

Within the TC-3 Town Center Zone, there are no minimum parking requirements and surface parking is not permitted. Parking requirements are reduced in the C1 Neighborhood Commercial, TC-1 Town Center Zone, and TC-2 Town Center Zone.
report_type: Reduce Parking Minimums, Eliminate Parking Minimums, Parking Maximums

report_summary: The downtown core area of the Central Business District (bounded on the north by 10th Street, on the east by 18th Avenue, on the south by the railroad and on the west by 26th Avenue) is exempt from off-street parking requirements.

For uses located within five hundred (500) feet of a public transit station or stop, the off-street parking requirements may be reduced by ten percent (10%). The Loop Trolley stops and stations are not included in this exception.

All uses located within the DMX Downtown Mixed-Use, LI Light Industrial, and HI Heavy Industrial districts are exempt from minimum parking requirements. In all districts, on-street parking spaces adjoining the development site may count toward the minimum parking requirement. This provision does not apply for single-family dwellings. Parking maximums exist for most uses.

Implemented--no parking minimums on commercial/industrial/multi-family townwide. Parking is "market based" where the applicant proposes a number of parking spaces and this can include parking spots in proximity (its "parkingshed") but not under its actual control.  

Proposed--revisions to single family zoning parking townwide to eliminate the parking minimums.  This is a part of an omnibus revision that is currently in a Plan Commission subcommittee and will likely go to the Plan Commission 1st or 2nd quarter 2023.
No off-street parking is required in the NC Neighborhood Commercial and CB Central Business districts.

No on-site parking is required for nonresidential uses in the CC Central Commercial District, unless specifically imposed as a condition of approval associated with a unique or unusual use or situation, as determined by the city council.

Within the MU Mixed-Use Overlay District, off-street parking is not required for commercial uses abutting the sidewalk unless the use exceeds ten thousand (10,000) square feet. A maximum of 1.5 parking spaces may provided per residential unit in the district.

In the Downtown Mixed-Use District in Fall 2020, parking minimums were eliminated for ground floor commercial uses and allow for reduced residential parking subject to special permit approval. A partial fee-in-lieu option exists via special permit.

Parking requirements may be reduced through frequent transit service, on-street parking or a travel demand management plan. In addition, parking maximums exist for all uses, but may be exceeded if the parking does not create additional impervious surfaces.
No parking lot may exceed the required number of parking spaces by more than 20%, except as approved by Community Development Director.
There are no parking minimums in the central business district, neighborhood parks, school play areas, or in vacant lots.
The B-2 Central Business District is exempt from minimum parking regulations.
It is no longer required to have off-street parking in the B-4 central business district, which encompasses the entire downtown.
The B-2 Downtown Business District is exempt from minimum parking requirements.

Parking maximums exist for all uses between 110 and 120 percent, but may be exceeded if the additional parking does not increase the impervious surface. Parking requirements may be reduced through bike parking, frequent transit, on-street parking and the provision of a transit plaza.
Off-street parking and loading requirements do not apply in the CBD (central business district) or on existing structures or uses at the time of passage of the regulations.

Within the five VC Village Center Zoning Districts, nonresidential uses may count on-street parking spaces towards satisfying off-street motor vehicle parking requirements. Further reductions are possible through a design exception.

The minimum number of required off-street parking spaces may be reduced by the number of on-street parking spaces abutting the property lines of the lot or parcel. Maximum parking applies to most uses.
Restaurant and retail uses have maximum parking limits.

All surface parking in the CR CM and CC downtown districts shall be shared parking. Because parking shall be provided by the city, private off-street parking is prohibited unless it existed prior to the establishment of these guidelines or is granted approval by the development review committee.

When the application of the off-road parking regulations results in a requirement of not more than three spaces on a single lot in the Commercial Districts, such parking spaces need not be provided, unless two or more uses are located on such lot in which case only one of the uses shall be eligible for the exemption.
The Central Business District is exempt from minimum parking requirements as well as accessory buildings in other districts.
Maximum parking allowed for a use may not exceed the parking minimum requirements in the "DMU" Downtown Mixed Use District and “EMU” Entertainment Mixed Use District.
Chelsea Central District does not have parking minimums and all retail/shopping centers have parking maximums.
No minimum off street parking required in the business district/Downtown.
Depending on the number of spaces required, parking may not exceed 105 to 120 percent of the minimums.

All Parcels in the CBD are exempt from off-street parking requirements.

Grants Pass is one of the 8 metro areas in Oregon subject to Governor Brown's 20-04 Executive Order regarding Climate Friendly & Equitable Communities. As of January 1, 2023, in accordance with the CFEC rules, Grants Pass does not currently require any off-street parking for any land use that is within a 1/2 mile of a frequent transit route. This area covers more than 85% of the city limits.

There is a proposal from two city councilors to eliminate on-site parking requirements for all food establishments in all zones (restaurants, bars, deli's, clubs with food service, etc.) in the City of Annapolis. Annapolis previously reduced requirements for restaurants in West Annapolis.

In all downtown zoning districts (D1, D2, D3, D4 and D5), off-street parking requirements may be reduced to 50% of the parking spaces otherwise required; provided the property is located within 600 feet of a municipal parking lot which is primarily available for public parking. Existing buildings not in compliance with the off street parking requirements may be remodeled, repaired, and structurally altered and may change use without complying with the minimum off street parking standards, except for a change in use to a nightclub or cabaret.
Uses and developments in the CBD, Central Business District, are not required to provide off-street parking facilities.

Wausau has completely elimited parking requirements in the downtown. Wausau has also reduced parking requirements by 50% in all commercial zones in the city. As well, Wausau has also enacted parking maximums for all uses in the city.

Commercial land uses in any commercial zoning district that are one thousand (1,000) square feet or less in gross floor area are exempt from the parking standards. Commercial land uses in the B-4 District are exempt from the parking standards.
Unless otherwise approved by the Community Development Director, the maximum permitted number of accessory off-street parking spaces is an additional 20% beyond the minimum requirement.

The total number of parking spaces provided for one-family, two-family or multiple family dwellings may not exceed the minimum requirements by more than fifty percent (50%) or four spaces, whichever number is greater.
Culver City officially adopted a zoning code amendment that abolishes all parking requirements city-wide, becoming the first in LA County to do so. Parking maximums are also being explored.

Parking maximums exist for all uses. Parking requirements may be reduced through the provision of bike parking. The minimum parking ratios are reduced by 25% by right within the Downtown Master Plan Overlay District and the Village Center Overlay District.

Off-street parking requirements do not apply to changes of use within existing buildings in the C-5 Downtown District. Minimum parking requirements must be met by any new residential construction projects.

Nonresidential uses under 10,000 square feet are exempt from parking mandates within the DT District. Parking requirements citywide may be reduced through on-street parking, public parking or bike parking. Maximum parking limits are set at 150% of the minimums for nonresidential uses.
report_type: Reduce Parking Minimums, Eliminate Parking Minimums, Parking Maximums

report_summary: Uses within the Downtown District and Virginia Street Corridor are allowed a reduction in the required number of parking spaces to provide 70% of the required number of spaces for a similar new building or use. When meeting these provisions would constitute a hardship or make the redevelopment of properties in these districts economically impractical, the City will receive a cash contribution in lieu of on-site parking facilities. In all districts, maximum parking may not exceed 125% of the minimum standards for parking lots with fewer than 200 spaces and 115% of the minimum standards for parking lots with greater than 200 spaces.

The off-street parking regulations do not apply to any use of new buildings or structures, or any existing principal building or structure which is enlarged or increased in capacity, when located with the areas bounded as follows:

a. Beginning at a point where the centerline of the right-of-way of First Street crosses the centerline of the right-of-way of Oak Street; thence Easterly along said centerline of Oak Street to a point where said centerline of Oak Street crosses the centerline of Seventh Street; thence Southerly along the said centerline of Seventh Street to a point where the
said centerline of Seventh Street crosses the centerline of Grove Street; thence Westerly along said centerline of Grove Street to a point where said centerline of Grove Street crosses the centerline of Second Street; thence Northerly along said centerline of Second Street crosses the Southerly right-of-way line of the Union Pacific Railroad; thence Westerly along said Southerly right-of-way line of said railroad to a point where said Southerly right-of-way line crosses the centerline of First Street; thence Northerly along said centerline of First Street to the point of beginning.

b. Beginning at a point where the centerline of the right-of-way of First Street crosses the centerline of the right-of-way of the Union Pacific Railroad right-of-way, thence easterly along the centerline of said railroad right-of-way to a point where said centerline intersects with the centerline of Second Street, thence southerly along said centerline of Second Street to a point where it intersects with the centerline of Grove Street, thence easterly along the centerline of said Grove Street right-of-way to the intersection with the centerline of the right-of-way of Fifth Street, thence southerly along said centerline of the right-of-way of Fifth Street to a point where said centerline intersects with the centerline of the right-of-way of Franklin Street, thence westerly along said Franklin Street right-of-way centerline to the point where said centerline intersects with the centerline of the First Street right-of-way, thence northerly along said First Street centerline to the point of beginning.
Developments cannot provide more than 15% above the required amount of parking unless the applicant can prove additional parking is needed.
No minimum off-street parking requirements for developments in the C-E Casino Entertainment District.

Principal permitted commercial uses in the C-3 Commercial District, and residential uses established as a permitted secondary, incidental or accessory use to a principal permitted commercial use in the C-3 Commercial District are exempt from minimum parking requirements.
No parking is required in the Central Business District or the East Florence Historic District.

Parking minimums do not apply to any parcel less than 5,000 square feet in area or for the rehabilitation or reuse of structures existing on October 15, 2020, within locally designated historic districts. Ten of the sixteen primary districts are exempt from minimum parking requirements. In districts where parking is required, a number of uses are exempt including ADUs, townhomes, upper story residential uses, government services, medical clinics, bars, and more. Parking maximums apply citywide. Parking requirements may be reduced with on-street parking, bike parking, proximity to transit, or a use meeting certain requirements in the Hillside Stability Overlay District.
report_type: Reduce Parking Minimums, Eliminate Parking Minimums, Parking Maximums
land_uses: All Uses, Industrial, Other, Residential, Medical, Commercial

report_summary: Within the B-1 Village Center District, the owner may, at the discretion of the Village Board, contribute to the Bartlett Public Parking Fund for the required number of parking spaces not provided.
Off-street parking is not required in any EA -CG Zone in a downtown area except for a permitted residential use, retirement home, hotel and motel.
No minimum parking requirements in Central Business District zoning district.
No minimum off-street parking is required in the B-5 Central Business District.
Parking requirements may be reduced through on-street and public parking. Maximum parking limits exist for office and retail uses.
The C-2 Central Business District is exempt from minimum parking requirements.
Woonsocket, RI does not require parking for non-residential uses in the Urban Commercial and Mixed Use districts.

Within the M-U Mixed Use District, on-street parking may count towards parking requirements for commercial or mixed use developments. Retail uses may reduce requirements if a transit shelter is provided. Parking maximums are set at 110% of the minimums for surface parking.
Parking maximums exist for all uses.
Commercial uses in the area shown on the map are exempt from parking requirements if they are located within 500 feet of a municipal parking lot.

Since at least 2008, the city has implemented a parking exemption for every use in some sectors, except for residential units. The exemption is applied by zones and they are mostly within the old pre-war downtown area.
Also, anywhere else in the city and for every uses, the parking requirement can be reduced by a maximum of 30% of the required number of spaces with a monetary compensation of 7500$ per missing spot. The city council decides if the reduction is accepted totally, partially or declined.
The B-2 Central Business District and the NC Neighborhood Commercial District are exempt from minimum parking regulations.

The D Downtown District and CCO-A Center City Overlay District A are exempt from parking mandates. The C Circle District and CCO-B Center City Overlay District B require 50% of the minimums. Parking maximums apply citywide to all uses except single-family and two-family dwellings.
report_type: Eliminate Parking Minimums, Reduce Parking Minimums

report_summary: Burlington, VT has eliminated parking mandates citywide and has maximums for many uses.

Where there is a municipal parking lot within 500 feet, the parking spaces required for non-residential uses and mixed uses may be reduced by ten percent of the total spaces in the municipal lot or lots. Where on-street parking exists on a street adjacent to a new or expanded use located within the Old Town District, the required number of off street parking spaces for the new or expanded use may be reduced by one space for each 25 feet of frontage on the street, up to a maximum reduction of five spaces.
Trelleborg eliminated parking requirements for new residential development in the city center.
The Central Business (B-3) Zone is exempt from off-street parking requirements.

Within the Downtown Creative District, no parking is required for the adaptive reuse of buildings listed or eligible for listing on the National or State Register of Historic Places or for ground floor uses on a Principal or Secondary Street. Parking requirements are reduced for uses in the TS Tyler Street Overlay District and the Smart Growth Overlay District.
There are no parking requirements in the Central Business District.
Parking maximums apply to most uses citywide.
Parking and loading requirements do not apply within the Central Business Performance (CBP) District.
Nonresidential uses, except for schools, do not have specified parking minimums. Instead, they must provide a parking demand needs assessment (PDNA) to be approved by the township.

The minimum parking requirements in the Riverfront Mixed Use District may be reduced by one motor vehicle parking space for every two bicycle parking spaces. Motor vehicle parking spaces may not be reduced by more than 10% of the total number of required motor vehicle parking spaces.

Parking minimum requirements for multifamily housing built for the elderly were reduced from 2 parking spaces per dwelling to 1 parking space per dwelling citywide. 

Parking minimum requirements for mixed-use and multifamily developments located in a special transit zone were reduced between 15-75% based on the distance from a transit stop.
Any property located in a C-3 Zone (Central Business District) is exempt from providing off-street parking.
Parking requirements for nonresidential uses in the B5 Central Business District are reduced by 50 percent.
Places of worship and schools other than State College are exempt from parking requirements citywide, while nonresidential uses in the B5 Central Development District are also exempt.

Uses and buildings located in the CBD-C, Central Business District-Core, are exempt from the minimum parking requirements. However, the City Council may require off-street parking to be provided for conditional uses in the CBD-C.
The MU-1 downtown mixed use zoning district is exempt from minimum parking requirements.

Off-street parking is not required in a CB Central Business Zone, except for hotels, motels and newly constructed residential buildings, and except for places of public assembly as determined by the Administrative Officer (such as bingo parlors, motion picture theaters, etc.).
For nonresidential uses in NBU Neighborhood Business Zones, off-street parking spaces are limited to no more than 60% of the minimum requirements.
Existing central business districts of municipalities are exempt from off-street parking requirements.

Off-street parking is not required for uses in the Central Business District except for buildings constructed or used for residential living units as the principal land use. The Central Business District is defined as the area bounded by Marr Street on the east, Merrill Street on the north, the East Branch of the Fond du Lac River on the west, and Western Avenue and Fourth Street on the south.

Small residential and business land uses within the Downtown Parking Zone (DPZ) are exempt from the minimum parking requirements. However, If a commercial land use has a gross floor area of five thousand (5,000) square feet or more, then the standards apply. If parking is required of a particular use, nearby on-street parking spaces and municipal parking lots may count towards off-street parking spaces. Commercial establishments within the DPZ shall not provide a number of off-street parking spaces that is greater than one hundred (100) percent of the parking requirement for that particular establishment's land use.
report_type: Eliminate Parking Minimums, Parking Maximums, Reduce Parking Minimums

report_summary: No off-street parking spaces are required in the central business zone.
In 2000, Winter Haven adopted a new Downtown Commercial zoning district that exempted all land uses within it from parking requirements.
Off-street parking in the C-1 district has been reduced by 50% for nonresidential uses. Nonresidential uses within 660ft. of a public parking lot will are exempt from off-street parking requirements.

Off-street parking is not be required in the CBD district for commercial uses. Parking maximums are set at 110 percent of the minimums unless any parking above the 110 percent threshold is pervious or is provided through use of structured parking.
Parking requirements may be reduced through bike parking, carpool parking, extra ADA accessible parking, or on-street parking.

Surface parking areas for multi-family, non-residential, and mixed-use development uses may not exceed 125% of the required minimum number of vehicle parking spaces. A ten percent (10%) reduction in the total required parking is permitted where car-sharing spaces are provided in a multi-family or mixed-use development. New uses in existing buildings on commercially zoned parcels are not required to provide parking if the new use would not result in a significant change of intensity relating to traffic and parking.

In the CBC Central Business Core District, CBOC Central Business Outer Core District, and CBOCR Central Business Outer Core Residential District accessory off-street parking is not required except for residential uses.
The CB Central Business District is exempt from minimum parking requirements.

No off-street parking is required for any structure in the C-4 central business district except residences. Citywide, the total number of parking spaces provided for a single-family, a two-family or multiple-family dwelling may not exceed the requirements by more than fifty (50) percent or four (4) spaces, whichever number is greater.

On December 18, 2023, Charlottesville eliminated parking mandates citywide. The city had previously eliminated parking minimums in the city center and a special university district. There was a zoning overlay that also eliminated mandates for smaller developments and reduced mandates for larger developments.
Parking maximums exist for most uses.
There are no minimum parking requirements in Roswell's C-3 (downtown) district.

Parking maximums are set at 125% of the minimums. Structured parking facilities are exempt from this maximum. Parking reductions are available for nonresidential uses when bike parking or shower facilities for bike commuters are provided.

Off-street parking requirements do not apply to any existing buildings located in the Downtown Business (C-2) District where no parking presently exists and there is no opportunity to provide it, except for certain residential uses. In all Zoning Districts except C-2, off-street parking requirements do not apply to a non-residential land use occupying 4,000 square feet or less and located within an existing structure. Parking requirements may be reduced through the provision of EV chargers. No use other than one or two-unit dwellings may provide parking in excess of 110% of parking minimums.

The Nelson County Zoning Code applies to the county and to all cities in the county. Uses within the Central Business District (B-2) may satisfy minimum parking requirements by using on-street parking spaces and public parking. Maximum parking is set for all uses.
The CBD District is exempt from minimum parking requirements.

The total number of accessory parking spaces provided for a single-family or multiple-family dwelling may not exceed the requirements for such use or for any equivalent new use by more than 50 percent or four spaces, whichever is greater.

No off-street parking is required in the B-4 Downtown Business District, although adequate on-street and off-street parking and unloading spaces must be demonstrated by the applicant for places of assembly, daycare centers, schools, and residences.

There are no on-site parking requirements in the CBD Central Business District. Parking requirements may be reduced in the CVD Corridor Village District.
Within the Neighborhood Reinvestment Overlay (NRO) District, single family dwellings, accessory dwelling units, and duplex dwellings are exempt from minimum parking requirements. Further reductions to the parking requirements apply to other uses. 
In all districts, when the expansion of a commercial or industrial building requires two (2) or less new spaces, no additional parking spaces are required. 
The city has a standing administrative decision by the Planning Director to reduce on-site parking requirements for low-income and elderly/disabled housing developments from 2 spaces per unit to 1.
report_type: Eliminate Parking Minimums, Reduce Parking Minimums

report_summary: Off-street parking requirements do not apply to all land uses within the Downtown Center and Commercial Neighborhood Zoning Districts.
Dunwoody has no minimum parking requirements. The city converted parking minimums into parking maximums in 2019.

Within the M2 and M3 Districts, parking requirements may be reduced when located near a bus stop or when bike parking is provided. In commercial and industrial districts, parking requirements may be reduced through proximity to transit, on-street parking, bike parking, mixed-use development, or carpool parking. Lots in the CD and CN districts that are under 10,000 square feet are exempt from the parking minimums. Parking maximums apply in non-residential districts.
report_type: Reduce Parking Minimums, Eliminate Parking Minimums, Parking Maximums

report_summary: Development in the Downtown (DT) District is exempt from the minimum off-street parking requirements.

There are no minimum parking requirements for land uses in the R/A, OS, IMX and CCMX Districts.

There are no minimum parking requirements for industrial, religious institutions, and some commercial land uses ('amusements [indoor & outdoor]'). 

Parking maximums are set as twice the minimum requirement. Exemptions to parking maximums can be applied to single/two family dwellings and if the parking areas exceeding the maximum requirements are installed using Low Impact Development (LID) treatment OR the minimum number of trees is 1 tree per 10 spaces.
Bozeman eliminated minimum parking requirements in the Midtown Urban Renewal District.
The Central Commercial (CC) District and the Central Parking Waiver Area (defined by Jefferson Avenue to Ontario Avenue and 7th to 9th Streets) are both exempt from minimum parking requirements.
Most nonresidential uses have parking maximums in addition to parking minimums.

Parking requirements may be reduced through the availability of frequent transit service, on-street parking or a travel demand management plan. Parking maximums exist for all uses in the MX-2 Neighborhood Mixed Use District and for shopping centers and retail stores in all districts.
In the Downtown P1 District, no parking is mandated. In the P2 district, parking mandates are Reduced by 30% for non-residential uses.

Commercial uses requiring one hundred (100) or more parking spaces may not provide more than four and one-half (4.5) spaces per one thousand (1,000) square feet of floor area unless otherwise approved through the special use approval process. Minimum off-street parking requirements do not apply in the DC Downtown Core District or DB Downtown Business District or the Fairview Concentrated Business District, except for residential uses, medical offices, dental or health practitioner offices, and any nonresidential uses requiring Village Council approval. Parking in all districts may be reduced through the provision of motorcycle parking, carshare service, or dedicated electric vehicle parking.
report_type: Parking Maximums, Eliminate Parking Minimums, Reduce Parking Minimums

report_summary: All properties located in the CD, Downtown Commercial district are exempt from minimum parking requirements. All properties located in the CDS, Downtown Commercial Support district may provide 50% of the parking spaces otherwise required upon certain conditions. Uses in all commercial, public/semi-public, and industrial zoning districts may count 20% of any public spaces within 300 feet of the property on which the use is located toward meeting the minimum number of required parking spaces.
report_type: Reduce Parking Minimums, Eliminate Parking Minimums

report_summary: No parking is required in the C-2 Central Business District. In all districts, reductions are allowed for on-street parking, bike parking, and nearby public parking. No non-residential use may provide more than 150% of the minimum required parking.
report_type: Reduce Parking Minimums, Eliminate Parking Minimums, Parking Maximums

report_summary: Parking maximums exist for most uses.
All development in the Urban Core Central Subdistrict is exempt from minimum parking requirements.
No off-street parking is required in the commercial C-3 district.
No car parking is required in the Downtown Business District and the Four Street Business District.
For any activity permitted by right in the Central Business District, accessory off-street parking is not required. In addition, parking maximums exist for commercial uses in the CBD.
Mooresville has removed parking minimums in its downtown district and established a new parking maximum of 125% of the minimum in all other zoning districts.

On March 10, 2022 La Crosse eliminated parking mandates for non-residential uses in Local Business, Commercial, and Community Business zones. Previously La Crosse had no parking requirements in Industrial zones, as well as exemptions for the downtown and uptown areas.

Off street parking facilities required for churches may be reduced by fifty percent (50%) where churches are located in nonresidential districts and within three hundred feet (300') of usable public or private off street parking areas.
There are no minimum off-street parking requirements for uses in the "B-1" central business district.
Non-residential uses in all zoning districts may not contain more than one hundred ten percent (110%) of the minimum number of parking spaces required.
The B-D Business Downtown District is exempt from minimum parking requirements.

Permitted business and office uses in the B-2 Central Business District are exempt from off-street parking requirements. This exemption does not apply to residential dwelling uses. Parking maximums apply to single-family and two-family dwellings.

Olympia enacted specific zone district requirements, eliminating residential parking minimums as well as minimums for all existing commercial buildings, and new commercial construction or expansion totaling under 3,000 square feet within the Downtown Exempt Parking Area. Non-residential uses may receive credit for on-street parking in all districts.
report_type: Eliminate Parking Minimums, Reduce Parking Minimums

report_summary: No off-street parking is required in the C-2 Retail Core Business District

Parking maximums exist for apartment buildings, residential uses in the Mixed Development District, and multiresidential uses in the Planned Commercial District. Parking requirements may be reduced through the availability of frequent transit, carshare services or bike parking. However, the area which would have been occupied by the eliminated parking spaces must be devoted to pervious surfaces, stormwater facilities, tree retention or native landscaping.

The first 3,000 square feet of gross floor area is exempted from minimum parking requirements for nonresidential uses in the Central Business District (CBD). Up to 25% of the number of public parking spaces within 400 feet of a proposed building in the CBD may be counted toward the required number of spaces. Citywide, bicycle parking may be substituted for required parking, while maximum parking is set at 130% of the minimums.
report_type: Eliminate Parking Minimums, Reduce Parking Minimums, Parking Maximums

report_summary:
Within the DC and DE Downtown zoning districts, a structure with less than 
 3,000 square feet on the ground floor is exempt from minimum parking requirements. All other uses in the districts have reduced requirements. The R-C2 Central Residential - Moderate Density, and R-C3 Central Residential High Density Districts have reduced parking requirements.
report_type: Reduce Parking Minimums, Eliminate Parking Minimums

report_summary: Mount Prospect lowered the parking requirement in the B-5 central commercial district and the B-5c central commercial core district.

Off-street parking is not required in the HC-1, or HC-2 district, or in the dense business area for residential land uses. Buildings within the South Palafox business district or the C-2A district may be exempted depending on size. Parking requirements may be reduced when bike parking is provided.
report_type: Reduce Parking Minimums, Eliminate Parking Minimums

report_summary:
Non-residential uses of 2,500 square feet or less of gross floor area of a standalone building or a nonresidential portion of a mixed use building in the commercial districts are exempt from all off-street vehicle parking requirements. Non-residential uses of 2,500 square feet of gross floor area or less located within a multitenant retail center are not eligible for this exemption. In these commercial districts, on-street parking spaces may be counted toward required off-street parking spaces for commercial uses. New on-street parking spaces may also be created to count toward required off-street parking.
In the DT-1 Downtown Central Sub-District, floor area equal to twice the area of the lot is subtracted from the gross floor area of a building and such reduced gross floor area is used to determine the number of off-street parking spaces required. 
In all districts, all uses located within one-half mile of a transit station (trains only) have reduced parking requirements. Furthermore, the Zoning Administrator may authorize greater reductions through the provision of a transportation management plan, the use of off-peak work schedules, or the provision of cash or in-kind financial incentives for employees commuting by carpool, car sharing, vanpool, and transit. At the discretion of the Village, a one-time fee may be paid in lieu of providing a portion of the required off-street parking.
report_type: Reduce Parking Minimums, Eliminate Parking Minimums

report_summary: Parking requirements do not apply in a block where 50% or more of the area was occupied by business or industrial structures at the time of passage of the zoning code.
Colton California has reduced parking minimums for commercial and residential in the downtown and mixed used neighborhoods but has not completely eliminated minimum parking in any area.

Accessory dwelling units and accessory nonresidential uses are not required to provide off-street parking in the RTD-9 District. Certain uses in the downtown districts are exempt as well. Numerous reductions are available depending on the district, size of project and other factors.
report_type: Reduce Parking Minimums, Eliminate Parking Minimums

report_summary: There are no minimum parking requirements in the Downtown District (C-4 District), limited requirements for business and apartment uses in the Aggieville District (C-3 District), and reduced parking requirements in the M-FRO District.
No minimum parking requirements. Full repeal adopted 12/13/22 effective 30 days later.
Parking requirements for all permitted uses are waived in the Central Commercial Zoning District and Warehouse Historic District.
Developments other than Small Residential Uses may provide no more than 200% of minimum parking required on site.
On June 14, 2023  Albany, OR eliminated parking mandates citywide for all uses. The reforms were instigated by Oregon's statewide reforms.

report_summary: Parking may be reduced by 10% for any parcel located within one-quarter mile of a transit stop. To qualify, the transit stop must be served by regular transit service on all days of the week and adequate pedestrian access must be available between the transit stop and parcel. Regular transit service must operate at least twice hourly between 7:30 a.m. and 6:30 p.m. on weekdays and once hourly after 6:30 p.m. Regular transit service must operate on Saturdays, Sundays, and holidays. In addition, two motorcycle/scooter parking spaces may be provided in lieu of one required automobile parking space. The maximum automobile parking space reduction under this provision is calculated at a 1:30 ratio (For every 30 required automobile parking spaces, one automobile space may be waived). The city of St. John's eliminated minimum off-street parking requirements for residential developments on Water Street or Duckworth Street having 5 Dwelling Units or less. Additionally, for all new change of use applications from non-residential to another non-residential use in the downtown parking area (where the floor area remains constant), the applicant will be exempt from all the minimum and maximum parking requirements in parking ratio table Section 8.3. 

Implementation of parking maximums city-wide:
The city of St. John's also has maximum off-street parking requirements for all land uses. 

Reduction of parking requirements in select downtown areas:

The Downtown Pomona Specific Plan, adopted August 5, 2019, removes minimum parking requirements for most existing buildings and many new ones. 

Specifically, the code states that "Parking requirements do not apply to the first two floors of any proposed development within the MU-CBD or MU-I districts. Moreover, the first two floors of any existing development within said boundaries are also not subject to parking requirements."

Since most of downtown Pomona's existing buildings are only one or two stories high, this provision removes minimum parking requirements for them. New one and two-story buildings are also exempt from parking minimums. Taller new buildings still have minimum parking requirements applied to the upper floors.

The plan also establishes maximum parking requirements, although this limit does not apply to parking spaces that are provided in parking structures.
