square feet in area may not surpass 115% of the minimum parking requirements.
Uses within the historic preservation overlay area, UP-1 and UP-2, SCD special character and ASN-A infill/low intensity district are exempt.

ADUs may be exempt from parking mandates when any of five criteria are met. In the DSP Downtown Specific Plan and TOD Transit Oriented Development zones, parking requirements may be reduced through bike parking, or a fee in-lieu of parking may be provided.
report_type: Reduce Parking Minimums, Eliminate Parking Minimums

report_summary: On-street parking spaces located adjacent to the site may be counted towards off-street parking requirements. A maximum of 50% of the required parking may be provided on-street.
Akron Ohio has no minimum requirements for parking for residential or commercial parking downtown.  Maximum allowed is one space per residence.

ADUs are exempt from parking requirements when located within one-half mile walking distance of a high-quality transit corridor, or a major transit stop, or there is a car share vehicle located within one block of the project. Within the Downtown Specific Plan Area, a fee-in-lieu of parking may be paid.
report_type: Eliminate Parking Minimums, Reduce Parking Minimums

report_summary: Nonresidential uses in the CB Central Business District are exempt from minimum parking requirements.

Parking minimums were reduced in 2021 for a variety of uses. There are also parking maximums city-wide. The city also included bike parking requirements. Parking minimums do not apply to most uses within the transit context (zones D-1, D-3, D-4, G-MU, TSA-C, UI, FB-UN2, FB-UN3, FB-SC, and R-MU)
report_type: Parking Maximums, Reduce Parking Minimums, Eliminate Parking Minimums

report_summary: Parking minimums in the OTC – Original Town Commercial District are fifty (50) percent of the standard parking requirements.
Parking requirements are reduced for commercial uses in downtown and neighborhood business districts and for residential uses in close-in residential districts.

Grand Rapids, MI eliminated minimum parking requirements in the TN-CC zoning district. Citywide, reductions in minimum requirements are available subject to Planning Commission approval based on special requirements.
report_type: Eliminate Parking Minimums, Reduce Parking Minimums

report_summary: Parking minimums have been repealed in the UU (urban use district), or the Central Business District/Downtown LR. It is implemented and applies to all uses.
ADUs may be exempted from parking requirements based on any of 5 conditions.
Parking requirements are reduced in the CBD Central Business District. On-street parking and bike parking may be used to reduce requirements citywide.
On-street parking may count towards parking requirements for residential uses.

There are no parking requirements in the Center City District (CCD). All applicants proposing to construct surface parking submit a parking demand analysis defining the number of spaces, why the off-street parking is required, and methods to accommodate potential deficiencies.
The B-5 Central Business District is exempt from minimum parking requirements.

No parking is required for uses in downtown (BG-6.0). Within the Commercial Corridor Overlay District (CCOD), parking minimums are reduced by 50% on average across most commercial/mixed use zoning districts. Parking maximums are generally equivalent to 125% of the normal base requirement.
report_type: Eliminate Parking Minimums, Reduce Parking Minimums, Parking Maximums

report_summary: All uses in the CRD and UPT districts are exempt from parking mandates. Parking requirements may be reduced for commercial and multi-family uses through bike parking. Parking maximums are set at 100% of the minimums.
report_type: Eliminate Parking Minimums, Parking Maximums, Reduce Parking Minimums

report_summary: The DT-1 and DT-2 districts are exempt from minimum parking requirements. Parking maximums apply to restaurants except in the DT-1 and DT-2 districts. A fee in lieu of required parking may be provided in the MU Mixed-Use District.
report_type: Eliminate Parking Minimums, Parking Maximums, Reduce Parking Minimums

report_summary: ADUs may be exempted from parking mandates if any of five conditions are met.

Off-street parking is not required in the B-4 Central Business District. Parking requirements were reduced in the B-3 Community Business District. Required spaces are reduced by 10% when within 1000 ft of transit. As of fall 2023, Birmingham is in the process of studying a reduction in parking requirements.
Oakville, Ontario has no minimum parkings in the downtown and reduced minimums in some reduction in parking in mixed-used zones.

Small nonresidential uses (except restaurant and eating and drinking establishments) in a historic district in the D-MX District are exempt from off-street parking and loading requirements.
Parking requirements are reduced in the CB District, GC District, and Downtown Districts. A change of use within an existing building within the Downtown Districts or Artisans & Industry Special District is exempt from parking requirements. Apartments and live-work units within 1/4 of a mile of a train station have reduced requirements. Citywide, a fee in lieu of required parking may be provided.
report_type: Reduce Parking Minimums, Eliminate Parking Minimums

report_summary: ADUs are exempt from parking mandates if any of five conditions are met.

Within the DX Downtown Districts, there are no minimum parking requirements, while the minimums for other districts are set as the maximums. Within the MX1 and MX2 Mixed-use districts, uses must provide parking equal to 60% of the minimum parking ratios and may not provide parking in excess of 120% of the minimum parking ratios. In all districts, parking requirements may be reduced for all uses through the provision of carshare parking, bikeshare facilities and motorcycle or scooter parking. Nonresidential uses may also count on-street parking spaces abutting the subject property towards the parking requirements.
report_type: Eliminate Parking Minimums, Reduce Parking Minimums, Parking Maximums

report_summary: Off-street parking is not required in the Central Business C-B District.

The City of Tacoma has a "Reduced Parking area" that encompasses most of the downtown core area, and effectively requires zero parking. Also all of the mixed use centers (which makes up the majority of all the new development in town) has low/no required parking. There are still parking requirements, but they have been greatly reduced and there is support at the policy level to expand the reduced parking area. As of early 2024, the Tacoma Planning Commission has proposed a significant expansion of the Reduced Parking Area along three transit corridors as part of the "Home in Tacoma" initiative.

A change of use in the Downtown Area is exempt from parking requirements. Certain nonresidential uses have reduced requirements in the Downtown Area. ADUs may be exempted if certain criteria are met as a result of state law.
report_type: Reduce Parking Minimums, Eliminate Parking Minimums

report_summary: Parking minimum requirements were reduced for the Transit-Oriented Development Overlay District, and bicycle parking minimums were introduced. Parking requirements may be further reduced with unbundled parking and in-lieu fees. The development code noted that as the transit system matures, they are looking to reduce or eliminate parking minimums. A 2017 Accessory Dwelling Unit Amendment reduced minimum parking requirements for ADUs, and prohibits minimums in certain qualified locations.
report_type: Reduce Parking Minimums, Eliminate Parking Minimums

report_summary: Parking requirements are reduced for most commercial uses in the CBD central business district and CR commercial-residential zoning districts.

The C-5 District is exempt from minimum parking requirements. Reductions are available for transit availability, structured parking, nonresidential on-street parking, and tree preservation. Parking maximums are set at 125% of the minimums.
report_type: Reduce Parking Minimums, Eliminate Parking Minimums, Parking Maximums

report_summary: ADUs are exempted from parking requirements when certain criteria are met as required by state law.

The City of Regina removed all minimum parking requirements within the Downtown. If any parking is voluntarily provided by a development any parking in excess of one stall per 50 square metres must be contained within a structured parking facility.

In center and corridor downtown, neighborhood retail zone, and FBC CA1, CA2, and CA3 zones, any new building or building addition with a floor area less than three thousand square feet is exempt from parking requirements. Maximum parking limits apply citywide.
On July 17, 2023, Spokane passed an interim zoning ordinance which removed parking minimums for housing located within 1/2 mile walking distance of transit stops.
On April 24, 2023 the Richmond, VA city council voted unanimously to eliminate parking mandates citywide.

Parking minimums were reduced in much of the city as part of a wider zoning rewrite, which was approved in June 2023, and goes into effect in December 2023. 
The MX-5 District is exempt from minimum parking requirements and minimums may be reduced through a variety of means.
Additionally, Parking Maximums were implemented for many purposes, including Multi-family Dwellings, Art Galleries, Community Centers, and Restaurants.
report_type: Reduce Parking Minimums, Eliminate Parking Minimums, Parking Maximums

report_summary: The Warm Springs/South Fremont Community Plan, adopted in July 2015, eliminates minimum parking requirements within the community plan area. The plan area is centered on the new Warm Springs/South Fremont BART Station.

Parking requirements are reduced in the downtown area. On-street parking may count towards parking minimums outside the downtown area. Within the Downtown Overlay District (DO) and the Downtown District (D), a fee in-lieu of required parking may be provided.
There are no mandates for most uses in the Urban Growth Center zones (large offices being one exemption).

Norfolk eliminated minimum off-street parking requirements for all non-residential uses and residential development of 24 multi-family dwelling units or less for properties within the Norfolk and Western Historic Overlay district.
Within the DT Downtown District, on-street parking may be used to satisfy requirements and the provision of parking that is publicly shared allows for a reduction in requirements.

In the Central Business district, Winston-Salem has no minimum parking requirements for high-density residential and office that is above first-floor retail. In all other areas, there are requirements.

In the MU-S District, an automotive thirty percent (30%) reduction of existing minimum parking requirements may be applied. There are no parking maximums for this land use.
land_uses: Commercial, Multi-Family Residential, High Density Residential

report_summary: Parking maximums apply to some nonresidential uses.
Within the South Norfolk Business Overlay District, certain commercial uses are exempt from parking mandates, while residential uses have reduced requirements.
report_type: Reduce Parking Minimums, Eliminate Parking Minimums

report_summary: Uses located within the Central Business District and the Arts and Entertainment District are exempt from parking mandates.

There are no provisions that require a minimum number of off-street parking spaces for all land uses. A TDM plan is required for new construction (5,000 square feet or more) that determines the number of on-street, off-street, and shared vehicle parking spaces.
Parking requirements are reduced for nonresidential uses in the TOD District when located near transit. Parking requirements are reduced for uses in the Urban Business Overlay District.
Parking and loading space requirements do not apply in a Base Mixed-Use District.

In 2022. St. Petersburg eliminated minimum parking requirements for residential housing units in the downtown core that have 750 square feet or less.

They also reduced minimum parking requirements by 10% for affordable housing units, ADUs, and other properties located within 660 feet of a high-frequency transit route.

There is no parking required in the Central District of Madison and in several other mixed-use and TOD districts. Some other districts waive parking requirements for new developments smaller than 10,000 square feet.

Jersey City has about a dozen planning districts (known as Redevelopment Plans) with no parking minimums, largely concentrated near PATH rapid transit and HBLR light rail stations. In fact, several of these districts have parking maximums. Examples include the Journal Square 2060, Colgate, Harsimus Cove Station, Grand Jersey, and Newark Ave Downtown plans.
report_magnitude: Transit Oriented, City Center/Business District, Main Street/Special

report_summary: Parking requirements for residential development within the R-A Redevelopment Area District are reduced by right, with additional reductions possible for all uses in the district through on-street parking.

There are no minimum off-street parking requirements for uses in the DC/Downtown Core, or DE/Downtown Edge, or for airports, community gardens, cemeteries, fairgrounds, hospitals, nature preserves, religious institutions, or schools.
In the UC/Urban Corridor districts, minimum parking requirements apply only to a new bars, taverns, dance or similar school buildings, restaurants, night clubs or similar entertainment uses, the addition of units to an existing residential structure; or the conversion of a residential structure to nonresidential use.
Parking reductions are available in the City’s nonresidential zoning districts (DC, DE, UC, C1 through C4, SC, NC, BTI, and I1 through I3) via on-street parking, bike parking, public transit access, and the use of pervious surfaces.
Parking maximums exist within the DC and DE districts, set at 50% of the minimums when provided as surface parking, or 100% of the minimums when provided in a parking structure.
report_type: Eliminate Parking Minimums, Reduce Parking Minimums, Parking Maximums

report_summary: There is no minimum parking requirement in the Mixed-Use Downtown (MD-) districts. Properties that are partly or entirely located within ¼ mile of Mixed-Use Downtown (MD-) districts or the centerline of the Virginia Street or Fourth Street bus rapid transit routes (measured in a direct line) may provide parking at 60 percent of the Level 1 parking district minimum.
report_type: Eliminate Parking Minimums, Reduce Parking Minimums

report_summary: Where a transit terminal is located on a shopping centre site, the number of required parking spaces for the shopping centre is reduced at the rate of one space for each 30m2 of site area used exclusively for the transit terminal. No off-street parking is required in the B6 District. Within the CR-1 and CR-2 districts, most uses are exempt from minimum parking requirements.
report_type: Reduce Parking Minimums, Eliminate Parking Minimums

report_summary: On-street parking may be counted toward the visitor parking requirement for developments in the Single Family Detached (SF-D), Single Family Attached (SFA), Mixed-Use and Multi-Family zoning districts.

Allowed uses in the CD Downtown Commercial District are exempt from providing off-street parking spaces. Within the PO Pedestrian-Oriented Overlay District, non-residential uses are exempt from providing off-street parking spaces. No off-street parking spaces are required for residential building projects of 10 units or less, for larger residential buildings, parking requirements are reduced. Within the Central-City Special Parking District, the minimum off-street parking requirement for multi-dwelling units is reduced. Within locally designated historic districts, no off-street parking or loading spaces are required for rehabilitation or reuse of existing structures. For new construction within locally designated historic districts, minimum off-street parking ratios are reduced by 50 percent.
No use may provide more than 150 percent of the minimum off-street parking, except through approval of an Alternative Parking Plan. Within the Pedestrian-Oriented Overlay, parking maximums are set at 100% of the minimums. Surface parking lots are prohibited in the Downtown Core District and Warehouse District.
report_type: Eliminate Parking Minimums, Reduce Parking Minimums, Parking Maximums

report_summary: ADUs are exempt from parking mandates when one of five criteria is met as required by state law.

On November 20, 2023, Durham eliminated parking mandates citywide for all uses. Durham previously had a set of parking ratios, but certain districts were exempted or only required to build a percentage of the ratio. There are maximums for all uses and in all districts based on a percentage of the ratio, as well.
Parking maximums are set at 125% of the minimums. A change of use within the CCD City Center District is exempt from parking mandates.
No parking is required for residential and non-residential land uses within a 1,200-foot radius of a light rail, PATH train or NJ Transit train station.

The BG Downtown Business/Government District is exempt from minimum parking requirements. Maximum parking is set at the minimum number of required off-street parking spaces plus 10%, which may be exceeded if conditions are met. Up to 10% of required parking may be permanently set aside for stormwater quality or quantity improvements provided that the minimum required parking is 100 spaces or greater. 
Parking requirements for infill nonresidential uses may have reduced requirements, and a change of use may be exempted after the passage of Zoning Case 2023-027 on January 8, 2024.
report_type: Eliminate Parking Minimums, Parking Maximums, Reduce Parking Minimums

report_summary: The O-1 Office District and B-4 Lincoln Center Business District are exempt from parking mandates. Multiple districts have reduced parking requirements. There is a proposal to eliminate parking mandates from most commercial and industrial uses citywide.
report_type: Reduce Parking Minimums, Eliminate Parking Minimums

report_summary: Anchorage eliminated all parking minimums citywide on Nov 22, 2022, effective January 22, 2023 per AO 2022-80(S), as amended.

No off-street parking is required for properties in the CB district or for the reuse or rehabilitation of a historic site or landmark. Nonresidential uses on lots with less than 60 feet of frontage are not required to provide parking unless such use exceeds 3,000 square feet. Parking requirements are reduced in the TN, MU-M, MU-H and CN districts. In the AO, NS, LIM, UMU, C-M, C-H and BP districts, mixed use and adaptive reuse projects have reduced requirements. Citywide, projects that connect with an existing or planned greenway may have reduced parking mandates.
report_type: Reduce Parking Minimums, Eliminate Parking Minimums

report_summary:
In designated "Parking Exempt Areas", minimum parking requirements have been reduced by percentages ranging from 50% - 100% specified in the Pittsburgh zoning code. 

Land uses within these boundaries may not exceed the minimum parking requirements otherwise stated in the zoning code.

Cincinnati uses a tool known as an Urban Parking Overlay, which is a zoning overlay that removes parking minimums completely within its boundary.  Cincinnati implemented and Urban Parking Overlay-- completely removing parking requirements-- in four neighborhoods: Central Business District, Over the Rhine, Pendleton (all of which are considered the "urban core") as well we parts of the Camp Washington neighborhood.

There are no requirements for a minimum number of parking spaces. Parking maximums apply to surface lots exceeding 15 spaces. 

Facilities that exceed 15 spaces shall not be created unless a demonstration of need. 

Projects exceeding 40,000 square feet are required to submit a TDM Plan (TDMP) for City Review. 

There are minimum bike parking requirements for all land uses.
Uses within the Downtown Parking Zone A are exempt from parking requirements. Uses within the Downtown Parking Zone B have reduced requirements. Parking maximums apply to most uses.
report_type: Reduce Parking Minimums, Eliminate Parking Minimums, Parking Maximums

report_summary: ADUs may be exempted from parking requirements due to state law if certain conditions are met.

Implemented in Downtown District: No Minimum Parking Requirement in Downtown St. Louis: In roughly 4 square miles in and around downtown St. Louis, St. Louis has never had a minimum parking requirement. This was most recently codified by the 1947 zoning code. The "I" Central Business District, "No parking regulations shall be required for this district". All land uses.
ADUs may be exempted from parking requirements based on five conditions. A change of use may be exempted in certain circumstances.
report_type: Eliminate Parking Minimums, Reduce Parking Minimums

report_summary: On-street parking spaces may be substituted for required off-street parking when located in a Legacy Neighborhood Overlay District, on a street with a posted speed limit of thirty-five (35) miles-per-hour or less, and not prohibited by the applicable road jurisdiction(s), which may have additional requirements.

ADUs are exempt from parking mandates. A change of use within an existing structure in a nonresidential zone, which is designated as a historic resource or a contributor to a historic district, is exempt from parking requirements. Parking requirements may be reduced by implementing TDM strategies to reduce VMT.
report_type: Reduce Parking Minimums, Eliminate Parking Minimums

report_summary: The Downtown district is exempt from parking and loading requirements.

The CBD Downtown Commercial District and properties in the CI Intensive Commercial District located east of U.S. Highway 181 and Upper Broadway Street are exempt from minimum parking requirements. Within the CR Resort Commercial districts, parking requirements are reduced by 50% except for residential hotel, motel and overnight accommodation uses.
report_type: Eliminate Parking Minimums, Reduce Parking Minimums

report_summary: There is no minimum parking requirement for uses within one-quarter mile from the Altamont Commuter Express (ACE) Robert J. Cabral Train Station or a proposed California High-Speed Rail station. Residential uses in the Downtown Core have a reduced parking requirement as well as all uses in the Magnolia Historic Overlay District. Properties within the Parking Improvement District No. 2001-1, bounded by Park Street on the north, Mormon Slough on the west, Sonora Street on the south, and the Union Pacific Railroad tracks on the east are exempt if the property pays into the district. Parking requirements citywide may be reduced through bike parking, carpool spaces, EV chargers, frequent transit, small infill projects or motorcycle parking.
report_type: Reduce Parking Minimums, Eliminate Parking Minimums

report_summary: On December 11, 2023, Durham County joined the city in ending parking mandates.

On August 25th, 2022 The Planning Commission for Lexington-Fayette County (merged Urban-County Government unanimously approved 8-0 a Zoning Ordinance Text Amendment to eliminate minimum parking requirements, establish bicycle parking standards, mitigate environmental impacts of parking lots with an increase in required tree canopy, lighting restrictions, and increased buffering/screening meant to discourage the over provision of parking without instituting parking maximums.

Final action by the Urban-County Council was taken on October 27th, 2020. The regulations were adopted by a 14-0 vote.
Honolulu County removed parking minimums for all uses in two of the most urbanized planning regions on Oahu, including Honolulu, and also removed parking minimums for all uses in TOD zones.

ADUs are exempt from minimum parking requirements depending on transit proximity, number of bedrooms, and other factors. Two-family dwellings are exempt based on transit proximity and carshare availability.
Off-street parking requirements are not required in the Central Business District for all land uses.

Within the CBD Central Business District, and the CD Channel District, parking requirements are reduced by right. Mandates may be further reduced through the provision of motorcycle parking, bike parking or carshare in both districts. In the CBD, a fee in lieu of parking may be paid. Surface parking is banned within the Waterfront Overlay.

On-street parking and public parking in the OA Original Aurora District may count towards parking requirements for commercial uses. Adaptive reuse projects are exempt from parking requirements in the OA District. Numerous parking reductions are available based on transit, bike parking and other factors citywide for all except multifamily uses.
report_magnitude: City Center/Business District, Citywide, Transit Oriented
land_uses: Commercial, Industrial, Other, Low Density (SF) Residential

report_summary: There are no parking minimums for the Central Business District (downtown and some nearby neighborhoods). This is implemented in the City Center, and applies to all land uses.

No parking minimum requirements in the Historic Core, part of the Historic Urban Neighborhood (HU-B1A) and Central Business District. Also exempt, in Historic Urban Neighborhood Districts: 1) all single-family and two-family dwellings on lots 30 feet or less. 2) a single-family or two-family dwelling on a blockface where 40% of those existing dwellings have no off-street parking. Also exempt: the first 3,000 square feet in gross floor area for commercial uses i the HMC-2 district, and the first 5,000 square feet in gross floor area for commercial uses in HU-B1, HU-MU and MU-1 Districts, except for shopping center configurations. Parking maximums are 150% of the minimums.
Parking minimums are reduced in the DB, DNO, and LCMUO Districts and on-street parking may count towards the minimums. Parking maximums are set at 100% of the minimums in the EDO District.

Tulsa Oklahoma has no parking minimums downtown for all uses.  In the CH District and MX District and surrounding areas downtown, parking minimums are reduced 50% compared to other districts.  Retail uses requiring more than two hundred twenty-five (225) parking spaces may not provide more than four (4) outdoor parking spaces per one thousand (1,000) square feet of floor area.

ADUs are exempt from parking mandates when located near transit or is a garage conversion. Parking requirements are reduced for uses near transit or for nonresidential uses that provide motorcycle parking. On-street parking may be counted towards the minimums for nonresidential uses or for guest parking of residential uses. Affordable housing has reduced parking requirements. Uses in the “central district,” “Old Town Kern,” and other mixed-use areas may have reduced requirements.
report_type: Reduce Parking Minimums, Eliminate Parking Minimums

report_summary:
No parking minimums in: Downtown district, Transit Village, Rapid Transit Corridors, and around the Main Street area.

Reduced parking minimums in all other parts of the city.

Increased minimum bicycle parking requirements across the city.
Minneapolis has no minimum parking requirements. Parking maximums exist for all uses, and in no case may a surface parking lot exceed 100 spaces.
Halifax removed all parking minimums in the Downtown Plan Area in 2009.
Oakland has no required parking in CBD, S-2, and D-LM zones.  There are parking maximums in those zones.

The City of Laval eliminated minimum parking requirements for certain zones city wide. It also established parking maximums and it greatly reduced parking minimums across many zone types (for example, some commercial zones now only need 1 parking space per 75 square meters, sometimes even less in more central zones, while it used to be 1 space per 10 sq.m).

In the business, apartment and office districts the number of off-street parking spaces may not exceed the required number by more than fifty percent (50%). Such maximum parking requirements do not apply to uses whose off-street parking requirements are allocated within a parking structure.

ADUs are exempt from parking mandates under certain conditions. Long Beach has reduced parking minimums for transit-oriented off street parking for residential and hospital use reducing parking from 25% to 50%.
report_type: Reduce Parking Minimums, Eliminate Parking Minimums

report_summary:
On 3/15/2022 Raleigh City Council voted 7-1 to eliminate parking mandates citywide and impose parking maximums on many uses.

In June 2021, Raleigh City Council directed staff to develop an ordinance to eliminate parking mandates and implement parking maximums. On February 8th, 2022 the Planning Commission unanimously approved the zoning change and it will now go on to city Council.

Raleigh currently has no parking minimum requirements in the Downtown District and in the Transportation Overlay District.
Miami repealed a significant portion of its parking reforms on April 28, 2022. Will take some time to determine the ongoing status.
report_type: Reduce Parking Minimums, Eliminate Parking Minimums

report_summary:
Minimum parking requirements have been eliminated for all land uses in the central business district (CBD) and neighborhood business districts (NBD). 

For TOD-1, there are no minimum parking requirements.
For TOD-2, TOD-3, TOD-4 the minimum number of required parking spaces is 50 percent of the specified minimum requirements.

There are two established parking exempt districts in which there is no additional off-street parking required; Downtown/Central business district and Old Colorado City. Parking may be reduced with approval in other districts.
report_type: Eliminate Parking Minimums, Reduce Parking Minimums

report_summary: There are no parking mandates in the downtown core and various levels of exemption for commercial and residential uses in several adjacent districts.

No parking is required within 1/2 mile of MARTA Stations and near more than a dozen activity centers (Special Public Interest Districts) for any uses except establishments that serve alcohol. No parking is required for any buildings built before 1965, citywide. Many districts exempt affordable housing from parking mandates. In February 2024, the city exempted most uses in the Beltline Overlay District.

Parking requirements are reduced when located near a BRT or LRT station. Parking requirements for community buildings may be reduced through the provision of bike parking, golf cart parking or motorcycle parking. On-street parking spaces located immediately adjacent to the frontage of properties in the EO, MX, DB, ME, PE, and DC districts or districts with a "-U" designator, may be counted toward required off-street parking for non-residential uses. Maximum parking is set at 125% of the minimums.

The City has adopted Program H8. Revisions to Parking Requirements.
The City shall consider further eliminating City-mandated parking minimums and explore instituting parking maximums along established transit corridors. Analysis, community outreach, and coordination with the City’s Parking Services Division will be initiated in 2021.

Recommended revisions to the Planning and Development Code’s parking regulations to be presented to City Council for consideration in 2022. 

There are currently no minimum parking requirements in the Central Business & Arts/Entertainment District for all land uses. In this district, commercial land uses have parking maximums.

Downtown Districts: No parking minimums for non-residential uses. Parking minimums reduced to .5 spaces per unit.

Mixed-Use District/Commercial Main Street: Require .75 spaces for every studio/one-bedroom apartment, 1 space per two-bedroom, and 1.5 per three-bedroom, plus one per guest per four dwelling units. Commercial uses require one space per 600 square feet.

Within the Downtown Parking District, parking requirements are reduced by right, a change of use is exempt from parking requirements, and the provision of public amenities or the payment of a fee in lieu of parking will reduce requirements further. 
Citywide, on-street parking may be counted towards certain residential uses, and nonresidential NRHP listings may be exempted. Additional reductions to parking requirements are possible through the provision of EV chargers, additional handicapped parking, bike parking, additional landscaping, or providing trash enclosures.
report_type: Reduce Parking Minimums, Eliminate Parking Minimums

report_summary: Albuquerque New Mexico has eliminated off street parking requirements in the downtown and SU-1 Transit Oriented Development.  They have also reduced parking minimums in many other areas and had on street parking account for off street parking by different reduction rates in areas like transit oriented developments.

Parking Minimums were reduced by 20% for all land uses in the City Centre, other than office and multi-family residential with underground parking, which received their own rates. Offices were reduced by 44% of the city-wide standard. Multi-family residential with underground parking was reduced to by 38% of the city-wide standard. Former parking minimums are now parking maximums in the City Centre.

There are no off-street parking requirements for uses located in downtown zoning districts (C9A) and uses located in a red redevelopment district. Land uses within 1,000 feet of a bus stop or within downtown boundaries are eligible for a 25% reduction in the number of parking spaces required. Required spaces may be satisfied by assets in a public lot or structure on a one-to-one basis, and must be located within 700 feet of the use.
Developments in the  C-1, C-1-E, C-1-VC, and C-5 districts are exempt from parking mandates. Parking maximums are generally 2X the minimum, citywide.

There are no minimum or maximum parking requirements for all uses in the Central Business District. There are maximum parking requirements for certain uses. There are opportunities to reduce the minimum parking required outside of the CBD if specific criteria are met.

No minimum off-street parking spaces are required in the CBD District or the SCBID District. Reduced parking ratios apply in the Uptown District and the Medical Overlay District. Within the University District Overlay, nonresidential uses are exempt from parking requirements, while residential uses have reduced requirements.
Parking requirements may be reduced for a variety of uses when located near transit, on-street parking, or public parking. Other reductions are available for bike parking, tree preservation, and pedestrian accessibility.
report_type: Eliminate Parking Minimums, Reduce Parking Minimums

report_summary: Within downtown Las Vegas, the first 2000 square feet of a nonresidential use is exempt from parking mandates. Parking minimums are reduced and parking maximums apply in downtown.
report_type: Eliminate Parking Minimums, Reduce Parking Minimums, Parking Maximums

report_summary: Portland has no parking mandates citywide for any uses. Prior to July 2023, the city maintained mandates that were only in effect in rare instances. As part of Oregon's Climate Friendly and Equitable Cities policy, the city purged the mandates from the code effective June 30, 2023.
Uses in the B5 and PC Districts and in any other district in the Central Business District area shall be exempt from off-street parking requirements.
The downtown plan area waives parking requirements for all development, regardless of land use.

The erection, expansion or use of any principal building or secondary structure located in the following districts does not require off-street parking:

A.Fringe Parking Overlay District.
B.NB Neighborhood Business District.
C.DBD Downtown Business District.
D.DTD-1 Downtown Transitional District Limited.
E.DTD-2 Downtown Transitional District General.
F.C-CBD Central Business District.
G.NC Neighborhood Conservation District, Tract 5
H.UD Urban Design Overlay, except west of North Classen Boulevard and in the Lincoln Boulevard Corridor Subdistrict.
I.BC Bricktown Core.
J.The Farmers Market District of the Scenic River Overlay Design District (SRODD).
Nashville repealed parking mandates in the Urban Zoning Overlay which is the entire old city of Nashville.  The old minimums in that zone are now maximums
Boston City Council passed a resolution in October 2021 to eliminate parking mandates for developments with more than 60% affordable housing. Boston also has citywide parking maximums
Parking requirements are eliminated in various zone overlays (D, SEFC, USN, CG, and MU-11 Zones). Washington, DC has reduced parking requirements near transit.
Exemptions exist for small uses near transit, affordable housing, or retail in mixed-use projects. Numerous reductions are available and parking maximums apply to most uses.
report_type: Reduce Parking Minimums, Eliminate Parking Minimums, Parking Maximums
land_uses: All Uses, Commercial, Low Density (SF) Residential

report_summary: Since 2008, 20% reduction allowed (anywhere in city) if building is mixed-use and we allow developers to double it with infill reduction, totaling 40%. Parking is not required in the Downtown zoning district.

Parking is currently not required for any non-hospital uses in designated Urban Centers and Station Overlay Areas, plus any properties within 1/4 mile of a frequent transit stop that lie inside Urban Village boundaries.

For commercial and multifamily residential zones outside of Urban Villages, parking requirements are reduced by 50% within 1/4 mile of frequent transit stops.

Map: https://www.seattle.gov/Documents/Departments/OPCD/Vault/RegulatoryReform/ParkingFlexibilityAreasMap.pdf. Dark and light grey areas have no parking requirements (except for hospitals), and yellow areas have 50% parking reductions.
report_magnitude: City Center/Business District, Transit Oriented, Main Street/Special

report_summary: No Off-Street Parking is required in the Mile Square Area or MU-4 District.
There are no parking mandates in the city of San Francisco for any use except Mortuary (8 spaces mandated). There are parking maximums for most uses.

No vehicle parking is required for any use in any TOD District, except for bars, restaurants, micro-breweries, microdistilleries, micro-wineries, and live performance venues within 200 feet of a single-family residential zoning district.
Columbus has eliminated all parking minimums and requirements in the Downtown planning area. In much of the downtown new accessory surface lots are prohibited.

For non-residential uses, there are no minimum parking requirements. Additionally, properties designated as historic and cultural landmarks are not subject to minimum off-street requirements and there are no minimum off-street requirements in the Central Business District ("H").

The maximum number of parking spaces shall not exceed 125% of the minimum parking requirement for all uses listed.
There are no parking minimums anywhere in the Downtown overlay district.

When the application of the off-street parking provisions results in a requirement of not more than three (3) spaces on a single zoning lot in any business, office research, or industrial district, such parking spaces need not be provided where the building is unmanned; however, where two (2) or more uses are located on a single lot, only one (1) of those may be eligible for the exemption.
Ottawa has zero parking requirements in the city center and no residential parking requirements for buildings less than 4 stories. Remaining parking requirements are relatively low.
The City of San Jose removed parking minimums for all uses citywide. The changes will go into effect in March 2023.
On November 2, 2023 Austin City Council voted 8-2 to eliminate car parking mandates citywide for all uses.

Minimum on-site parking requirements have been removed from Edmonton’s Zoning Bylaw, allowing developers, homeowners and businesses to decide how much on-site parking to provide on their properties based on their particular operations, activities or lifestyle.
Parking minimums do not apply to the ML Mount Lemmon zone or the RVC Rural Village Center zone adjacent to the ML zone.

Montgomery County has several parking districts in which parking mandates are waived if a tax to support district parking is paid. In recent years, the tax has been reduced to zero, thereby making parking minimums effectively zero in several downtown business districts in the county.
On September 26, 2023, Fairfax County passed an ordinance to reduce parking minimums primarily for multi-family residential uses near transit.
The City of Calgary has removed minimum parking requirements for non-residential uses from the Land Use Bylaw.

Within the Central Area Districts, no parking is required of buildings which existed prior to June 26, 1967 or for ground-floor retail and personal service uses except for establishments serving alcohol or commercial amusement uses. Additionally, no parking is required for the first 5,000 square feet of ground-floor floor area for a restaurant without drive-in or drive-through service.

As of February 2024, there is a proposal to eliminate most parking minimums in the city.
Maine eliminated parking requirements for Accessory Dwelling Units and also limits parking minimums for affordable housing developments in growth centers to no more than 2 space for every 3 units
report_type: Reduce Parking Minimums, Eliminate Parking Minimums

report_summary: Residential developments within 1/2 mile of a current or planned major transit stop are exempt from minimum parking requirements. Any provided parking in market-rate developments with more than 4 units must be rented or leased separately (unbundled) from the dwelling unit. Commercial uses are exempt from requirements in transit priority areas and commercial neighborhoods citywide.
The Downtown "D" District is exempt from minimum parking requirements.

There are no minimum parking requirements for residential land uses in certain residential districts (RSA-4/5/6 and RM-1). There are no minimum parking requirements for residential, office, and retail land uses in certain commercial zoning districts (CMX-2/2.5, CMX-3, CMX-4/5).

No car parking is required for non-residential uses in the Downtown and Warehouse districts. Reductions for residential and commercial parking requirements are automatic near light rail stations. Parking maximums are in place for most uses, but there are ample opportunities to increase them.

The Ashland and Cherryland Business District Specific Plan regulates a 246-acre area along two major streets in unincorporated Alameda County. Within the plan area, there are no minimum parking requirements for restaurants and small retail establishments. In most zones within the plan area, there are also no minimum requirements for offices, “general commercial”, gas stations, car washes, and automobile sales, rental, and repair establishments. For land uses where minimum parking requirements still apply, the requirements are generally lower than the County’s standard requirements. The plan sets maximum parking requirements for most land uses. At many residential developments, the plan also requires the unbundling of parking costs and the provision of designated spaces for carshare cars.

Parking Minimums abolished in the borough of the Sud-Ouest for 99.9% of the territory (everywhere except in zone 415, in Griffintown, where citizens won a referendum to prevent minimums from being abolished on their block. Eliminations were also made in Ville-Marie borough and Plateau-Mont-Royal borough.

There are no minimum parking requirements within the Central Business District (CBD); There are no parking requirements within primary Transit Oriented Development (TOD) streets and a 50% reduction along secondary TOD streets. In 2019, minimum parking requirements were also removed in parts of the Midtown and Downtown East neighborhoods.

There are no minimum parking requirements for certain nonresidential uses within the Downtown Zoning District, which are also subject to specific maximum requirements. 

In certain districts (B,C, or D), the minimum parking requirement for residential uses may be reduced by 50% if the property is within 1,320 feet of a CTA rail station, a Metra rail station, OR along a high frequency bus line corridor, or 2,640 feet of other specified bus line corridors that is also along a designated 'pedestrian street or a 'pedestrian retail street'.

In other districts (B,C, D or M), the minimum parking requirement for non-residential uses may be reduced by 50% if the property is within 1,320 feet of a CTA rail station, a Metra rail station, OR along a high frequency bus line corridor, or 2,640 feet of other specified bus line corridors that is also along a designated 'pedestrian street or a 'pedestrian retail street'.

The parking may be reduced by 100% if it is approved as a special use.
On December 15, 2021 Toronto repealed car parking mandates citywide for all uses.

Connecticut adopted Public Act 21-29, a statewide zoning reform law that reduces minimum parking mandates, among numerous other reforms.

In May 2020, Governor Ned Lamont, as part of a pandemic response executive order, temporarily suspended statewide parking requirements for existing restaurants, allowing them to utilize their parking lots for outdoor dining.
The Cornfield Arroyo Specific Plan, passed in 2012, has no minimum parking requirements for projects in the area.

In July 2022, Oregon's Land Conservation and Development Committee adopted permanent rules which will require 61 cities in the state's 8 metro regions to eliminate parking mandates near high frequency transit service by 1/1/2023. Additional rules will require more comprehensive reforms in following years. 

HB2001, passed in 2019,  legalized “missing middle” housing types – such as duplexes, fourplexes, and townhomes – in medium and large cities statewide. The new rules implementing the law “hold mandatory parking ratios at or below one parking space per home.”

HB2001 rules apply to any city with a population greater than 10,000 people and to any city in a metro area with more than 1,000 people. Approximately 58 Oregon cities fall under this definition.

Medium cities had to comply by 6/30/2021 and Large cities must comply by 6/30/2022.

Additionally, ADUs are legal, statewide, and cities may not require parking for ADUs.
report_type: Eliminate Parking Minimums, Reduce Parking Minimums

report_summary: The National Policy Statement - Urban Development (NPS UD) required councils to remove provisions for a minimum number of on-site car parks from district plans through a non-notified process, to allow more intensive urban development with less space taken up by car parks, leading to better utilisation of urban land.
The People Over Parking Act, introduced in January 2024, would prohibit parking minimums statewide.

As of February 2024, a bill has been introduced that would prohibit a county or municipality, on or after January 1, 2025, from enforcing minimum parking requirements for property that is within a metropolitan planning organization.

In 2019, the city removed a mandate for a minimum of one space per housing unit for buildings within 800 meters of transit, and replaced it with a maximum of one parking space for every four residential units.  It is also now mandatory to offer bike parking facilities at a minimum of one space per housing unit.

NYC consists of 5 boroughs with over 8 million people. NYC has no parking minimums in most of Manhattan, and reduced requirements (with no requirement for certain types of housing) in several other dense neighborhoods around the city. 

In the Manhattan Core (Community Districts 1-8), no off-street parking is required. The maximum amount of off-street parking allowable is determined by the proposed use and Community District. 

On September 21, 2023, Mayor Adams proposed removing minimum parking requirements for housing citywide. In order for the change to take effect, it will have to pass the Uniform Land Use Review Procedure and would not become law until at least fall 2024.
Mexico City eliminated parking minimums in July 2017. Previous minimum requirements became parking maximums. Developers must pay in-lieu fees for parking in excess of 50% of the parking maximums.
The City of São Paulo eliminated parking mandates citywide for all land-uses in 2014. This was part of the strategic master plan of July 31, 2014.
As of 2024, a bill has been proposed to eliminate county parking requirements for transit oriented development, and reduce requirements near transit or near public parking.
report_type: Reduce Parking Minimums, Eliminate Parking Minimums

report_summary:
AB2097, signed into law in September 2022, prohibits cities and counties from enforcing parking mandates within 1/2 mile of high quality transit service. There are avenues for city's to enforce multi-family residential mandates on a case-by-case basis, but also a backup exemption for developments which include affordable housing.

Previous California laws limited local parking mandates. 

Senate Bill 35, adopted in 2017, has streamlined the approval of thousands of affordable homes near transit. The law grants these projects relief from local parking mandates.

Senate Bill 9 signed into law in 2021, makes it legal statewide to build up to four homes on most lots that are currently zoned for single-family homes only. Cities cannot require more than one parking space per home for projects built under the law.
